# Procfile - place this in your project root
# Railway reads this to start both processes from the same deployment

web: node server.js
worker: node lead-radar/scheduler.js


# ── DEPLOYMENT CHECKLIST ──
#
# 1. Copy these files into your project:
#    /lead-radar/scanner.js
#    /lead-radar/scheduler.js
#    /lead-radar/sources/reddit.js
#    /lead-radar/sources/upwork.js
#    /lead-radar/sources/instagram.js    (stub, safe to ignore for now)
#    /public/radar/index.html            (the radar UI)
#
# 2. Paste routes from server-radar-routes.js into server.js
#    - Add the RADAR_DB_PATH, loadRadarLeads, saveRadarLeads helpers
#    - Add the 4 /api/leads routes
#    - Add the /radar GET route
#
# 3. Create leads-radar.json in project root:
#    echo "[]" > leads-radar.json
#    Commit it to git (Railway needs it present)
#
# 4. Update your Procfile (above) and commit.
#
# 5. Railway will automatically start both web and worker processes.
#    You can monitor them separately in Railway's logs tab.
#
# 6. Visit https://raoufpx.com/radar to access the radar UI.
#    It will prompt for your ADMIN_KEY (same key as your existing dashboard).
#
# ── NOTES ──
#
# - leads-radar.json is separate from your existing leads.json
#   to keep the promo funnel data isolated from prospecting data.
#
# - The worker writes to leads-radar.json on disk.
#   If Railway's filesystem is ephemeral (it is for hobby plans),
#   consider migrating to Railway's Postgres add-on for persistence
#   across restarts. For now, JSON on disk works for testing.
#
# - Reddit scanning works immediately, no credentials needed.
#
# - Upwork RSS may return limited results depending on their feed availability.
#   Test manually: curl "https://www.upwork.com/ab/feed/jobs/rss?q=photographer+dubai"
#
# - Instagram is a stub until you set up a Meta Developer app.
